# Terraform Rules

Project conventions and existing toolchain configuration override these defaults unless unsafe.

## Code Organization
- Use modules for reusable components
- Separate environments (dev, staging, prod)
- Prefer separate state per environment for real infrastructure. Use workspaces only when the project has already standardized on them.
- Keep resource definitions in logical files

## Best Practices
- Use variables for all configurable values
- Use outputs for important resource attributes
- Document variables and outputs with `description`
- Mark outputs as `sensitive = true` when they expose secrets, tokens, or credentials
- Implement proper state management
- Use remote state backends (S3, etc.)
- Version lock provider versions

## Security
- Never commit secrets or sensitive data
- Use Terraform variables or secret management
- Implement least privilege IAM policies
- Use data sources for existing resources
- Enable encryption at rest

## Resource Management
- Use data sources to reference existing resources
- Implement proper tagging strategy
- Use lifecycle rules appropriately
- Plan before applying changes
- Review terraform plan output carefully

## State Management
- Use remote state backends
- Enable state locking
- Backup state files regularly
- Use terraform import for existing resources
- Avoid manual state file edits
- Commit `.terraform.lock.hcl` unless the project intentionally manages provider locks another way

## Testing
- Use `terraform fmt` for formatting
- Use `terraform validate` for syntax checking
- Use `terraform plan` to preview changes
- Run `tflint`, `tfsec`, `checkov`, or the project's configured IaC scanners when available
- Test in non-production environments first
- Review changes in pull requests
